A prime number is a natural number that is divisible only by itself and 1.

Here's a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number:

```js
function checkPrimeNumbers(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    let num = arr[i];
    if (num > 1) {
      for (let j = 2; j < num; j++) {
        if (num % j === 0) {
          break;
        }
      }
      if (j === num) {
        console.log(num + " is a prime number!");
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Here's an example of how to call this function:

```js
let arr = [2, 3, 5, 7, 11];
checkPrimeNumbers(arr);
```

This function will iterate through each number in the array, check if it's a prime number, and if it is, it will print the number to the console.

